# Cursor rules management

## File and structure

- Rules live under `PROJECT_ROOT/.cursor/rules/` as kebab-case `.mdc` files.
- Use `.mdc` extension with YAML frontmatter (`description`, `globs`, `alwaysApply`).
- **Target under 200 lines per file** — all rule content is loaded into the model context, consuming tokens. Shorter rules are applied more reliably. Split at 200 lines.
- One concern per file; avoid mixed-topic blobs.

## Frontmatter quality

- `description`: write it for the "Apply Intelligently" mode — the agent reads it to decide relevance. Make it specific: `"Testing conventions — AAA pattern, mocking, TDD anti-patterns"` beats `"Testing rules"`.
- `globs`: use precise patterns scoped to the smallest relevant file set.
- `alwaysApply: true`: only for rules that are truly universal across every task and every project. Every `alwaysApply: true` rule adds to the baseline token budget for all sessions.

## Content quality

- Be specific and actionable; vague rules ("write good code") are ignored by the model.
- Prefer bullet lists and short headers over prose paragraphs.
- Do not duplicate common conventions the AI already knows (npm, git, standard library usage).
- Reference real files from the codebase using `@filename` rather than copying their contents.

## Load order

- Cursor loads `alwaysApply: true` files in lexicographic order. Use numeric prefixes (`00-base.mdc`, `01-core.mdc`) when order of alwaysApply rules matters.
- Glob-scoped rules have no guaranteed order — write each to be self-contained.

## Maintenance

- Update rules when repeated agent mistakes, new stack conventions, or new patterns emerge.
- Deprecate outdated rules explicitly; remove or replace rather than leaving contradictory active versions.
- Prefer fewer, stronger rules over many fragmented micro-rules that repeat the same idea.
